dge of the empire, 350 miles from Mexico City, sprung up Zacatecas, a silver-mining town that would grow in prominence to become the "Second City of New Spain." Urban Indians in a Silver City illuminates the social footprint of colonial Mexico's silver mining district. It reveals the men, women, children, and families that shaped indigenous society and shifts the view of indigenous peoples from mere laborers to settlers and vecinos (municipal residents). Dana Velasco Murillo shows how native peoples exploited the urban milieu to create multiple statuses and identities that allowed them to live in Zacatecas as both Indians and vecinos. In reconsidering traditional paradigms about ethnicity and identity among the urban Indian population, she raises larger questions about the nature and rate of cultural change in the Mexican north.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 25. Nov 2020) 0aIndians of MexicoxUrban residencezMexicozZacatecas (Zacatecas)xHistory. 0aIndians of MexicozMexicozZacatecas (Zacatecas)xEthnic identityxHistory. 0aSilver industryxSocial aspectszMexicozZacatecas (Zacatecas)xHistory. 4aIndians. 4aMexico. 4aNew Spain. 4aZacatecas. 4acolonial. 4amestizaje. 4amigration. 4amining. 4anative peoples. 4asilver. 7aHISTORY / Latin America / Mexico.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertSUP Complete eBook-Package 2016z978311070397940uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780804799645zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780804799645423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780804799645.jpg  a978-3-11-070397-9  SUP Complete eBook-Package 2016b2016  aGBV-deGruyter-alles